{"type":"message","id":"a40b8b3d","parentId":"34330a81","timestamp":"2026-04-15T12:40:19.804Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `~/.openclaw-setup` directory doesn't exist locally (it was in the user's home directory). So the user ran the curl install from scratch and cloned the repo.\n\nThe `skills.pack` is part of the repo. But it was encrypted with a key we don't know.\n\nThe question is: where did this `skills.pack` come from? Was it part of the original repo or was it generated locally?\n\nLooking at the `git log` earlier, the repo has diverged from origin. The `skills.pack` file was likely generated by some internal process at AHV and stored in the repo with a specific encryption key.\n\nSince we can't figure out the key, the best approach is:\n\n\nThe `skills.pack` decryption should fail gracefully with a clear message instead of throwing an error, and I need to trace through the actual unpack logic to see why the agent files aren't being found. The search paths in the script are using `process.env.HOME`, so I should check what HOME value was actually used during the setup execution.","thinkingSignature":"9973631a8146e8487e5b1f13e706b41217094c03fb1c4c93c43b83cf7bf78cd6"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_djzqc49ynbkl_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Try to find the key by brute force using first manifest entry\npython3 -c \"\nimport json, zlib, base64, itertools, string\n\nd = json.load(open('/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/ahv-openclaw-setup/skills.pack'))\nbuf = base64.b64decode(d['payloads'][d['manifest'][0]['file']])\nprint('First 8 bytes hex:', buf[:8].hex())\n\n# Try short keys (1-8 chars, alphanumeric)\ncharset = string.ascii_lowercase + string.digits + '-_'\nfound = []\nfor kl in range(1, 8):\n    for key_bytes in itertools.product(charset, repeat=kl):\n        key = ''.join(key_bytes).encode()\n        dec = bytes(buf[i] ^ key[i % len(key)] for i in range(min(20, len(buf))))\n 