{"type":"message","id":"7b6a032e","parentId":"4699da5b","timestamp":"2026-04-15T12:42:28.484Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The script decrypts correctly now. Let me also fix the agent files search path issue. Looking at the user's output again, all agents showed \"No source agent files found\". But the files exist at `/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/{agentId}/`.\n\nWait - I need to check if maybe the issue is that when the user runs setup, the `HOME` environment variable points to a different home directory. For example, if the user runs as a non-root user, `HOME=/home/username`, and the source files are at `/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/{agentId}`. \n\nThat would definitely cause the search to fail. The script defaults to `~/.openclaw` if no custom path is specified, but the source files are at `/root/.openclaw/...`. So the real question is what path the user actually entered during setup—if they just pressed Enter and accepted the default, the script would search in the wrong location entirely. I'm realizing the search paths are checking multiple locations for the agent files — the repo directory, the `.openclaw` subdirectory, and a `.openclaw/workspaces` path — but the actual files seem to be in a different location than what these paths are looking for. So the source files are actually at `/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/senior-backend`, which means the second search path should find them unless `HOME` is pointing somewhere unexpected. Let me trace through what could cause all the search paths to fail — maybe `fs.existsSync()` is broken, or the paths aren't being constructed correctly.\n\nThe user entered `$HOME/.openclaw` when prompted, but I need to check how the path substitution logic handles that variable to see if it's resolving to the right location.","thinkingSignature":"e9bfa77f0695ca3ca9c796499bf24508606485cad5c555d62c34830bbe244b85"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"