{"type":"message","id":"41e536ec","parentId":"5fc3d8b9","timestamp":"2026-04-16T01:42:21.285Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Even the \"plain compress\" test (without XOR) is failing! This means `zlib.compress()` itself is producing data that can't be decompressed. But that should be impossible since zlib.compress always produces valid zlib data.\n\nWait, let me check if the issue is that zlib.compress produces a different format than zlib.decompress expects. In Python, `zlib.compress` produces raw deflate data (no zlib header), while `zlib.decompress` by default expects zlib-wrapped data (with header).\n\nActually no - in Python:\n- `zlib.compress()` produces zlib-wrapped data (with zlib header `0x78 0x9c` or similar)\n\n\n- `zlib.decompress()` expects zlib-wrapped data by default\n\nSo that's not the issue either. Let me look at the actual error more carefully - \"incorrect header check\" means the first few bytes are wrong, which suggests the data might be truncated or corrupted before decompression even starts.\n\nActually, I think I see it now. When I call `zlib.decompress()` on the base64-decoded data, the issue is that `bytes(dec)` creates a bytes object from the bytearray, but then `zlib.decompress()` expects the exact format that `zlib.compress()` produced. Let me trace through what's actually happening with the compressed output. I'm wondering if there's a `wbits` parameter mismatch between compress and decompress—`zlib.compress` uses `wbits=15` by default, but I should verify that `zlib.decompress` is expecting the same format. Let me also check the actual compressed data to see what format it's using, and then I'll run the round-trip test on a specific file to compare against what worked in the original pack.","thinkingSignature":"12c0c074b903d7ce9267bed1ca7756d4c09f4289c67a1fb3fc17c0c99398b19a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lvkw2yz2riul_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/ahv-openclaw-setup && python3 << 'PYEOF'\nimport os, json, zlib, base64\n\nSKILL_KEY = \"ahv-openclaw-2026\"\nSKILL_KEY_BYTES = SKILL_KEY.encode()\n\n# Debug: test compress round-trip for actual file\nwith open('agent-defs/agile-product-owner/AGENTS.md', 'rb') as f:\n    content = f.read()\n\nprint(f\"Content size: {len(content)}\")\nprint(f\"Content type: {type(content)}\")\n\n# Compress\ncompressed = zlib.compress(content)\nprint(f\"Compressed size: {len(compressed)}\")\nprint(f\"Compressed hex: {compressed[:8].hex()}\")\n\n# Decompress plain\ntry:\n    dec = zlib.decompress(compressed)\n    print(f\"Plain round-trip OK: {len(dec)} bytes, match={dec==content}\")\nexcept Exception as e:\n    print(f\"Plain round-trip FAIL: {e}\")\n\n# Now XOR encrypt then decrypt (full cycle)\nout = bytearray(len(compressed))\nfor i in range(len(compressed)):\n    out[i] = compressed[i] ^ SKILL_KEY_BYTES[i % len(SKILL_KEY_BYTES)] ^ (i & 0xff)\nencoded = base64.b64encode(bytes(out)).decode()\n\n# Decode and decrypt\nbuf = base64.b64decode(encoded)\ndec = bytearray(len(buf))\nfor i in range(len(buf)):\n    dec[i] = buf[i] ^ SKILL_KEY_BYTES[i % len(SKILL_KEY_BYTES)] ^ (i & 0xff)\nprint(f\"Decrypted size: {len(dec)}, hex: {bytes(dec[:8]).hex()}\")\n\ntry:\n    final = zlib.decompress(bytes(dec))\n    print(f\"Full round-trip OK: {len(final)} bytes, match={final==content}\")\nexcept Exception as e:\n    print(f\"Full round-trip FAIL: {e}\")\n\n# Test: what does the JS encrypt produce? Let's compare with the original pack\nimport subprocess\nresult = subprocess.run(['git', 'show', 'efb7680:skills.pack'], capture_output=True)\norig = json.loads(result.stdout)\nfirst_file = orig['manifest'][0]['file']\nprint(f\"\\nOriginal pack first file: {first_file}\")\norig_buf = base64.b64decode(orig['payloads'][first_file])\nprint(f\"Original encrypted size: {len(orig_buf)}, hex: {orig_buf[:8].hex()}\")\nPYEOF"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"A